
         Cathexis — Security-Hardened Nefarious2 IRC Daemon
         ===================================================

Cathexis is a security-hardened fork of the Nefarious2 IRC daemon (based
on ircu/IRCu2). It retains full compatibility with the P10 server protocol
and existing Nefarious2 networks while adding modern IRCv3 capabilities,
systematic memory safety improvements, and comprehensive security hardening.

Version: 1.0.0
Base: Nefarious2 (u2.10.12.14)
Protocol: P10
License: GNU General Public License v1+

WHAT CATHEXIS ADDS
==================

Security Hardening
------------------
  - All sprintf() calls in runtime code replaced with ircd_snprintf() or
    snprintf() for bounds-checked formatting
  - All dangerous strcpy() calls replaced with ircd_strncpy() for bounded
    string copying across 20+ files
  - SSL certificate verification callback now logs unverified connections
    to aid deployment auditing
  - SETNAME command includes CR/LF injection filtering
  - Separate client/server handler pattern for SETNAME to prevent error
    reply leakage across server links

IRCv3 Capabilities (11 new)
----------------------------
  - cap-notify         CAP 302 implicit notification
  - server-time        ISO 8601 timestamp tags
  - account-tag        Account name on messages
  - message-tags       Full IRCv3 message tag framework
  - echo-message       (pending implementation)
  - invite-notify      Channel invite notifications
  - chghost            Host change notifications
  - setname            Realname change (with SETNAME command)
  - batch              Message batching framework
  - labeled-response   Request/response correlation
  - standard-replies   FAIL/WARN/NOTE error format

  These join the existing capabilities: multi-prefix, userhost-in-names,
  extended-join, away-notify, account-notify, sasl, tls.

New Commands
------------
  - SETNAME    Change realname (GECOS) with IRCv3 capability gate

Protocol Improvements
---------------------
  - IRCv3 message tag (@tags) prefix parsing in client message parser
  - CAP 302 version tracking infrastructure (con_capver field)
  - Feature flags for all new capabilities (F: line toggleable)

EXISTING NEFARIOUS2 FEATURES
=============================
  - Asynchronous event engines: epoll (Linux), kqueue (FreeBSD),
    /dev/poll (Solaris), poll() fallback
  - F: (feature) lines with runtime GET/SET configuration
  - P10 account persistence across netsplits
  - Full SASL support (PLAIN, EXTERNAL)
  - SSL/TLS for client and server links
  - Extended ban types (~a, ~c, ~j, ~n, ~q, ~r, ~m, ~M)
  - WEBIRC support for web-based clients
  - G-line, Shun, Z-line network ban management
  - Host cloaking
  - GeoIP integration (optional)

INSTALLATION
============

  ./configure --prefix=/path/to/install
  make && make install

See INSTALL for detailed instructions. For high-load tuning, see the
platform-specific sections below.

COMPATIBILITY
=============

Cathexis is fully compatible with:
  - P10 protocol servers (Nefarious2, ircu2)
  - IRCv3 clients (HexChat, WeeChat, irssi, The Lounge, etc.)
  - Existing Nefarious2 configurations (ircd.conf)

Server-to-server links work with unmodified Nefarious2 servers. New
IRCv3 capabilities are only sent to clients that negotiate them via CAP.

CONFIGURATION
=============

All new capabilities are enabled by default and can be toggled via F: lines
in ircd.conf or the SET command:

  F:CAP_server_time:FALSE       # disable server-time
  F:CAP_message_tags:FALSE      # disable message-tags
  F:CAP_setname:FALSE           # disable setname
  F:CAP_echo_message:FALSE      # disable echo-message
  (etc.)

SSL RECOMMENDATIONS
-------------------

For production deployments, enable certificate verification on server links:

  F:SSL_VERIFYCERT:TRUE
  F:SSL_NOSELFSIGNED:TRUE

Without these, server-to-server TLS accepts any certificate (logged by
Cathexis but not rejected by default for backward compatibility).

GENERAL PERFORMANCE HINTS
==========================

  - Use an OS with async event engines (Linux epoll, FreeBSD kqueue)
  - Dedicate the server to IRC, minimize other services
  - Tune kernel file descriptor limits for high connection counts
  - Run local caching DNS for fast resolver lookups
  - Synchronize clocks via NTP across all network servers

RUNNING ON LINUX
================

Linux 2.6+ with epoll provides optimal performance. Set file descriptor
limits appropriately:

  ulimit -n 16384

Or configure via /etc/security/limits.conf.

RUNNING ON FREEBSD
==================

kqueue is used automatically on FreeBSD. Increase system limits:

  sysctl -w kern.maxfiles=16384
  sysctl -w kern.maxfilesperproc=16384

See the original Nefarious2 docs for detailed FreeBSD kernel tuning.

